The first virtual provider will come to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The telephone market in the Czech Republic is well mature, the Czech suppliers offer virtually all the services they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Still, there is something missing here - a virtual provider who forces the classic to lower prices.
Maybe this one won't wait for a long time.
That the Czech mobile telephone providers are working on the most expensive in Europe, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
This also confirmed by the Telecommunications Authority ČTú, which made it clear that the price for a SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in regulating roaming fees, there is so likely a paradoxical situation - for some customers of the Czech mobile telephone providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a fight response.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxous, in Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile telephone providers like to blame for the excessive competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) also often commits Pavel Dvořák, who had often said in the past that there was no room for another supplier in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with his own network has no more special opportunities (and he would probably hardly find spectrums).
But there is another option - a virtual provider.
Just the entry of virtual providers to the mobile market resulted in a significant reduction in prices, which the classic mobile telephone providers had to respond to.
There were similar votes on the market in the UK before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile.
However, it has shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't need to look for examples for long.
In February we reported about the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just a half year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus rise to the fiveth largest provider in the country.
Behind mobiling, the Penta financial group has U:phone in Czech Republic, among other things.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for construction, operation and entertainment of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap telephone conversations and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half a cheaper price than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good shock to put on a non-climbing target group.
This provider is specifically addressed to men.
"Echt guys choose Mobilking - the provider that they like and which they can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a concept similar to that in Poland could take foot in the Czech Republic.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer."
In the Czech Republic, mobile telephone providers are unaffected.
However, it is almost certain that when a virtual mobile provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very hopeful.
It will be more likely to enter the market of Mobilking in other countries of our region," says a telephone call for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, press speaker of the Penta financial group.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile telephone providers in the Czech Republic are not specially affected by this thought.
