We have not yet been addressed by a subject with a complex and serious project in this area," says his Declaration for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Srše州 from the Press Department of Telefónica O2.
Further suppliers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare conformity with the O2 statement: "We have not yet found a viable and both-sided project on which we could continue to build."
And she adds: "In the network of T-Mobile, hardly a virtual provider will appear until the end of the year.
At this moment we must have already had a specific offer to think so short-term."
Vodafone focuses rather on the fulfilment of the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický says: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the field of sharing costs and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we view from the customers as the best.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is looking for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet."
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
Mobile telephone providers' operations are easy to understand, another provider called more competition, this would lead to lower prices and thereby also to a decline in profits.
So why should such a competitor be made easier to enter the market?
That the providers can pull on a string when it comes to something, also the long hin and here proves to be the creation of U:fon.
The strongest pressure toward ČTU went from the company T-Mobile when U:fon came to the market.
