The psychology of the supply - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, the buyers tend to spend more and therefore overestimate the error offered.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now managed to discover the neurological-economic foundations of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an increase on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play lottery while the others participated in a gambling action - in both cases the active brain regions of the volunteers were examined through functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to gain money, but an increased activity of the Stratum, a complex below the brain barbecue, was measured in the case of losers of the auction, where the survival of the opponent plays a major role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore argued that the increase in prices could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the Striatum.
In order to support their these, the economists in the research group have conducted additional investigations to follow up the money.
In this case, three groups should be involved against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the real value of the product and then they made their efforts.
Another group was also promised $15 reward, in case they come out of the game as winners.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the case of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was therefore merely that the emphasis was on one of the winnings, while the other was on the loss.
However, as proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "contrary to losing" group were ready to make more efforts than those in the control or the "winning" group.
"These results can be derived from no previous economic theory.
They have just justified the behavior observed in auctions with the joy of gaining or avoiding risks.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaginary neurological process, so that we have now a third explanation prepared" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of the University of New York Economics.
Hepatitis: When should the doctor be visited?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed under the leading causes of death.
The number of infected persons is estimated to be a hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and yellowness are common, but the irritations and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the bacteria, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. by contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body liquids (e.g. sperm, scissor or spray).
Travelers are recommended for vaccination against viruses A and B, at least there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A are shown about two or three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and fracture.
After that, the yellowness appears on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the cure may last for up to two or three weeks.
Around the world, about 1 million people die every year of the diseases caused by hepatitis B such as liver cancer and hepatic cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only every tenth infected in drug treatment is.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their illness, as the infector devours the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular control tests, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more frequent: those who have been taking a blood transfusion before 1991, drug-dependents, and tattoos.
At present, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the home doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Timely detected, the disease is healable, the virus can be eradicated, thus baning the risk of infection and preventing the formation of cancer.
On September 30, the world day of hepatitis, 2004, is the first time organised by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen the consciousness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their origin and the importance of early detection.
