Intelligent car imitates the flight of Hummel
What would be the best method for developing new technologies to prevent accidents if not to imitate natural obstacle sensors?
For example, the bees.
The CEATEC in Japan presented a amazing project in which the Nissan engineers of Hummeln were inspired to create new accident preventive systems.
In collaboration with the Tokyo University, Nissan built the biomimetic system controlled by authoroboters by type BR23C, a mini car, equipped with the properties of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that prevents any collision.
In the flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective sign", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology-PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composed eye of the bee, which can see in every direction and in an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
To imitate the function of the composed eye, the researchers took the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles before the BR23C in a 180 degree vision field within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor, which immediately initiates the collision prevention process.
The obstacle is registered in seconds, and the autorobot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees by rotating the tyres around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this manöver takes place instinctively.
"If not, the authorobot could not respond quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," explained Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the "Mobility Laboratory" and the autoroboter project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately as this technology corresponds to the innerst and most vulnerable part of the protective shield - a layer that is currently considered unavoidable within the accidents.
The whole process must reflect the bees' behavior when they differ from other bees.
And this has to last in the fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, it can not occur up, down, or even diagonal - it can only be two-dimensional, just towards the turnability of the tyres.
While the bees are infinitely open to other bees, the researchers were able to use only the rotation, acceleration and braking at the autoroboter.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer lifetime than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent reaction, and less on the processing of data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device must only process some inputs per second and respond accordingly.
It does not have to store this, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction using previous manöver, so that it uses only a handful of KB Memory.
No Gigabyte and Megabyte Heavy Memories are required.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision prevention technology, which will be serially in production within the next ten years, according to the assessment of Nissan.
Another application could find the technology at GPS satellite navigation by consciously directing the car driver around obstacles and thus leading it to the target.
